				<p>
					When <m>m</m> is true, <m>p</m> is false, and <m>r</m> is false—the fourth row of the table—then the hypothesis <m>m \land \neg\,p</m> will be true, but the conclusion (<m>r</m>) is false, resulting in an invalid conditional statement; every other case gives a true result.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
		<p>
			Again, this result might seem very abstract. 
			Here is a real-life situation that could be modeled by <m>(m \land\neg\,p)\rightarrow r</m>.
		</p>
		<p>
			Suppose <m>m=</m> we order meatballs, <m>p=</m> we order pasta, and <m>r=</m> Ruba is happy.
			The statement <m>(m \land\neg\,p)\rightarrow r</m> is then, <q>if we order meatballs and don't order pasta, then Ruba is happy</q>.
			If <m>m</m> is true (we order meatballs), <m>p</m> is false (we don't order pasta), and <m>r</m> is false (Ruba is not happy), then the statement is false, because we satisfied the premise, but Ruba did not satisfy the conclusion.
			In all other cases the statement is true.
		</p>
	</subsection>

